  "prompt": "What is Electromagnetic spectrum?",
  "response": "The electromagnetic spectrum is the range of all possible frequencies of electromagnetic radiation. It encompasses various types of waves with different wavelengths and energy levels, including:\n\n1. Radio waves\n- Longest wavelengths\n- Low frequency\n- Used for communication\n- Examples: AM/FM radio, TV broadcasts\n\n2. Microwaves\n- Shorter wavelengths than radio waves\n- Used in cooking, communication, radar\n\n3. Infrared radiation\n- Heat radiation\n- Used in thermal imaging, remote controls\n\n4. Visible light\n- Wavelengths human eyes can detect\n- Different colors correspond to different wavelengths\n\n5. Ultraviolet (UV) radiation\n- Higher energy than visible light\n- Can cause sunburns\n- Sources include sun and tanning beds\n\n6. X-rays\n- High-energy radiation\n- Can penetrate soft tissues\n- Used in medical imaging\n\n7. Gamma rays\n- Highest energy\n- Shortest wavelengths\n- Produced by radioactive decay\n- Used in cancer treatment\n\nKey characteristics:\n- All electromagnetic waves travel at the speed of light\n- Waves differ in wavelength, frequency, and energy\n- Follows inverse relationship between wavelength and frequency",
